            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Rebecca Goldstein\u2019s life has been a study in deliberate self-construction. Raised in a quiet, sensible suburb of Chicago by an accountant father and a teacher mother, her childhood was stable and loving, but bereft of ambition\u2019s sharp edges. They instilled in her a formidable work ethic, which she channeled into a Business Administration degree from the University of Illinois. While her parents hoped she would find a secure corporate job nearby, Rebecca felt a pull toward the frenetic energy of the west coast, arriving in San Francisco in the early 2000s, just after the first dot-com bubble had burst.\n\nShe found a city nursing a hangover, which suited her grit. She took a junior marketing job at a struggling brick-and-mortar retailer trying to build an online presence. While others were fleeing tech, Rebecca dove in, learning the nascent field of e-commerce from the ground up. Her career became her anchor. A key turning point came in her mid-thirties when a long-term relationship dissolved. He wanted to move to Marin and raise a family, a life that felt like a return to the suburbs she had consciously left behind. The painful split solidified her identity as an urban professional, and she doubled down on her career, eventually landing her current role as Director of E-commerce for a major apparel brand.\n\nToday, Rebecca\u2019s life is a curated tapestry of San Francisco experiences. She lives in a meticulously decorated one-bedroom apartment in Hayes Valley, a neighborhood whose chic boutiques and central location she adores. Her days start with a foggy morning run past the Painted Ladies at Alamo Square before she catches the Muni for the 3.8-mile ride to her SoMa office. Her social life revolves around a tight-knit circle of friends\u2014her chosen family\u2014with whom she explores the city's culinary scene and takes weekend hikes in the Headlands.\n\nWhile professionally fulfilled, Rebecca secretly dreams of a life less digital. She has a potter\u2019s wheel tucked into a corner of her apartment, a recent passion that offers a tactile escape from screens and spreadsheets. Her future aspiration isn't a C-suite title, but something quieter: the hope of one day having a small ceramics studio, selling her work at a local market, and building something with her own hands."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers the cab ride from SFO in 2002. News reports had painted a picture of a ghost town, but what she saw was a city catching its breath. Standing on a windy corner with her two suitcases, a wave of calm washed over her. It wasn't a sparkling promise land, but something better: a place with scars, a place that wouldn't judge her for having to fight for her footing. In that moment of gray, indifferent fog, she felt she could finally build a self of her own making.\n\n2.\nHer first real victory wasn't a promotion, but a single email notification around 2 AM at her grim first office. \"Your order has been confirmed.\" The struggling retailer\u2019s first-ever online sale. She had coded the checkout page herself through trial and error. In the quiet hum of the server, she felt a profound sense of creation. She hadn't just gotten a job; she'd built a tiny, functioning piece of the future. It was the first time she felt truly anchored to the city.\n\n3.\nIt was over a bowl of pasta in North Beach, about ten years ago. He was painting a picture of a yard in Marin, of weekend farmer's markets and good schools. Rebecca felt a cold dread, realizing he was describing her parents\u2019 life, the very thing she\u2019d fled. The heartbreak was immense, but beneath it was a harder, clearer feeling: a fierce, territorial love for her city life. In that moment, she chose the view from her own fire escape. The grief forged her independence into steel.\n\n4.\nTwo years ago, perched on a bluff in the Marin Headlands with her friends. They were breathless from the hike, sharing a thermos of coffee as the fog peeled back to reveal the entire city, a jewel box across the bay. There was no talk of careers or deadlines, just easy laughter. Looking at their faces, then at the distant skyline of her home, Rebecca understood. This was her family. This shared view, this chosen circle, was the life she had built just for her.\n\n5.\nLast winter, her hands slick with wet clay, she finally felt it. After weeks of lopsided failures, the spinning lump in front of her found its center, rising into a wobbly but true cylinder under her palms. The city noise, the endless emails, the performance metrics\u2014it all dissolved. There was only the hum of the wheel and the cool, responsive earth. It wasn't an achievement for a resume, but a quiet, powerful promise of a different kind of life, one she could shape with her own hands."
